Quotient Spaces

DEF : For a linear subspace 𝒴 ∈ 𝒳, x ∼ y if x − y ∈ 𝒴. [Equivalence]

  • x ∼ x
  • x ∼ y ⇒ y ∼ x
  • x ∼ y, y ∼ z ⇒ x ∼ z

DEF : (𝒳 modulo 𝒴) 𝒳|𝒴 = {[x] = {y ∈ 𝒴 : y ∼ x} : x ∈ 𝒳}.

  • [x] + [y] = [x + y]

DEF : (Linear maps) 𝒯 : 𝒳 → 𝒳* is a linear map if 1) 𝒯(x + y) = 𝒯(x) + 𝒯(y) and 2) 𝒯(αx) = α𝒯(x).

  • 𝒴 ⊆ 𝒳 is linear subspace, and then 𝒯(𝒴) = {𝒯(x) : x ∈ 𝒴} is a linear subspace.
  • 𝒴* ⊆ 𝒳* is a linear subspace, and then 𝒯−1(𝒴*) = {x ∈ 𝒳 : 𝒯(x) ∈ 𝒴*} is a linear space.

DEF : (Isomorph) 𝒳 and 𝒳* are isomorphic if ∃𝒯 : 𝒳 → 𝒳* bijection.

DEF : (Convex) 𝒦 ∈ 𝒳 is convex if x, y ∈ 𝒦, α ∈ [0, 1], αx + (1 − α)y ∈ 𝒦.

  • 𝒴1, 𝒴2 ∈ 𝒳 are convex subsets, and then 𝒴1 + 𝒴2 is convex.
  • 𝒦θ, θ ∈ ℐ are convex, and then ∩θ𝒦θ is convex.
  • 𝒦θ, θ ∈ ℐ are convex and totally ordered, and then ∪θ𝒦θ is convex.
  • 𝒦 is convex $$ 𝒯(𝒦) is convex.
  • 𝒦* is convex $$ 𝒯−1(𝒦*) is convex.

DEF : (Convex hull) 𝒮 ⊆ 𝒳, CU(𝒮) = ∩θ𝒦θ for all convex sets 𝒦θ ⊇ 𝒮. [Smallest convex set containing S]

Linear Spaces

DEF : 𝒳 is a linear space over a field 𝕂 (ℂ or ℝ) if 𝒳 is a set with 2 operations + and ⋅ (scalar multiplication).

  • +: x, y ∈ 𝒳 ⇒ x + y ∈ 𝒳
    • Commutative: x + y = y + x
    • Associative: x + (y + z) = x + y + z
    • Group: ∃0: 0 + x = x; ∃−x: −x + x = 0
  • ⋅ : x ∈ 𝒳, α, β ∈ 𝕂 ⇒ αx ∈ 𝒳
    • Commutative: (αβ)x = α(βx)
    • Distributive: (α + β)x = αx + βx, α(x + y) = αx + αy
    • 1: 1 ⋅ x = x

DEF : 𝒴 ⊆ 𝒳 is a linear subspace if x, y ∈ 𝒴, α ∈ 𝕂 such that αx + y ∈ 𝒴.

  • {𝒴θ : θ ∈ ℐ} is a set including linear subspace of 𝒳, then ∩θ ∈ ℐ𝒴θ is a linear subspace of 𝒳.

DEF : {𝒴θ, θ ∈ ℐ} is totally ordered if θ1, θ2 ∈ ℐ 𝒴θ1 ⊆ 𝒴θ2 or 𝒴θ1 ⊇ 𝒴θ2.

  • {𝒴θ : θ ∈ ℐ} is a totally ordered set including linear subspace of 𝒳, ∪θ ∈ ℐ𝒴θ is a linear space.

DEF : 𝒮 ⊆ 𝒳, linear span of 𝒮 is LS(𝒮) = ∩θ𝒴θ for 𝒴θ ⊇ 𝒮. [Smallest linear space containing S]

Seg03 - Eigenvalue and Eigenvector Decomposition of the Discrete Fourier Transform

Preliminaries

DEF : c(n) = col[c(0), …, c(N − 1)] ∈ ℂN is even iff c(n) = c(−n) and odd iff c(n) = −c(−n) with the definition of c(−n) = col[c(0), c(N − 1), …, c(1)].

Lemma 1 : There exists an orthogonal basis for ℂN consisting of v = [N/2] + 1 even sequences and N − v odd sequences.

  • Proof : An orthogonal basis can be constructed as follows: For N being even, there exists u(n) = col[0, …, 0, 1, 0, …, 0]. So there are (N − 2)/2 + 2 = N/2 + 1 even sequences. In the meantime, the number of odd sequences is (N − 2)/2 = N/2 − 1.

    For N being odd, there exists u(n) = col[0, …, 0, 1, 1, 0, …, 0]. So there are (N − 1)/2 + 1 = (N + 1)/2 even sequences. In the meantime, the number of odd sequences is (N − 1)/2.

    Therefore, there are even sequences and ⌈N/2 − 1⌉ = ⌊(N − 1)/2⌋ odd sequences whenever N is odd or even.

Lemma 2 : The eigenvectors of F are either even or odd sequences.

  • Proof : Assume the eigenvector of F is x such that Fx = λx. we have . The orthogonality yields Thus, αi = 0 for λ ∈ {−j, j} and βj = 0 for λ ∈ {−1, 1}. So x is either odd or even.

Theorem 1 : If l is even then Fl ± l is an eigenvector of F with eigenvalue ±1. If l is odd then jFl ∓ l is an eigenvector of F with eigenvalue ±j.

  • Proof : For l being even, F(Fl ± l) = F2l ± Fl = l ± Fl = ±(Fl ± l). For l being odd, F(jFl ∓ l) = −jl ∓ Fl = ±j(jFl ∓ l).

Digital Computation of the Fractional Fourier Transform (1996)

The FrFT has been widely used in a lot of fields, especially in communications. However, the operations with respect to the continuous domain can lead to considerable computational complexity. To mitigate this issue, several papers have considered the proposal of discrete FrFT (DFrFT). To start with, we simply provide the sampling-based form.

Sampling-based DFrFT

There are three primary papers delving into this topic.

  • Kraniauskas directly sampled the time and fractional Fourier domain.
  • Ozaktas derived the efficient and accurate DFrFT.(prevalent)
  • Pei defined another DFrFT form.(prevalent)

Comm. NL-CSS - part 02

Posted on 2025-08-27 Edited on 2025-09-01 In Communications , Non-linear Chirps

  • Q - Algorithms for resolving the coefficients of polynomial phase of non-linear chirps

  • A1 - ESPRIT for Polynomial-Phase Signals (PP-ESPRIT)

    Idea. Successive finite differencing of a polynomial-phase signal turns it into a cisoid with a Vandermonde structure; then apply ESPRIT to get coefficients in closed form.

    Sketch for a second-order chirp

    1. First difference: .
    2. Form a Hankel/Toeplitz data matrix from Δx[n]x[n], compute its signal subspace (SVD).
    3. Apply ESPRIT shift-invariance to obtain the cisoid “frequency”. Its slope across n yields α, and the intercept gives f0.
    4. Estimate A, ϕ0 by LS on x[n] with known α, f0.

    Pros. Super-resolution, no grid search, excellent for short data records.

    Cons. Needs decent SNR and careful model order (typically 1).

  • A2 - Phase Unwrapping + Weighted Least Squares (WLS)

    Idea. Unwrap the instantaneous phase and fit a quadratic directly.

    1. Compute ϕ̂[n] = arg x[n] and unwrap.
    2. Solve

    minϕ0, f0, α ∑nw[n](ϕ̂[n] − (ϕ0 + 2πf0n + παn2))2,

    with robust weights w[n] (e.g., Tukey/Huber).

    1. Closed-form via normal equations or QR.

    Pros. Analytic, fast, no transforms.

    Cons. Needs good SNR/initialization; use smoothing or short-time averaging before unwrapping.

  • A3 - Fractional Fourier Transform (FrFT) Ridge Maximization

    Idea. A linear FM becomes a tone after a rotation of the time-frequency plane; maximize concentration to read off α.

    1. Sweep FrFT order aa (rotation θ = aπ/2) and find a⋆ that maximizes spectral sharpness (e.g., kurtosis/peakness) of ℱa{x}|.
    2. Convert a⋆a^to chirp rate αvia the FrFT convention you use (the α ↔︎ θ formula depends on your normalization).
    3. De-chirp and estimate f0, ϕ0 as in #1.

    Pros. Very intuitive and robust for broad-band chirps.

    Cons. Be meticulous about FrFT normalization to map θto αcorrectly.

  • A4 - Radon/Ambiguity-Domain Hough Methods (RAT/Radon-TFD)

    Idea. The quadratic chirp ridge is a curve in the TFD or ambiguity plane. Radon/Hough integration along candidate curves yields a sharply peaked accumulator at the true α.

    • Build Wigner–Ville (smoothed) or spectrogram.
    • Integrate energy along quadratic curves parameterized by α; the maximizer gives α.
    • Then de-chirp and estimate f0, ϕ0.

    Pros. High resolution; resilient to moderate noise and partial occlusions.

    Cons. Heavier compute unless you use multiscale/coarse-to-fine search.

    Practical, no-nonsense recipe (works great)

    1. **PHAF for α*: pick a small set of lags τ∈{2,3,4}{2,3,4}, compute PHAF, take the dominant peak → α^.
    2. De-chirp: z[n]=x[n]e−jπαn2z[n]=x[n]e{-jn^2}.
    3. ESPRIT or Prony on z[n]z[n]: get super-resolved f^0f_0.
    4. Amplitude/phase LS: solve z[n]≈Aej(ϕ0+2πf0n)z[n]A e^{j(_0+2f_0 n)} for A,ϕ0A,_0.

    This gives all coefficients analytically, typically with far better than FFT-bin accuracy from short data.

    Implementation tips

    • Windowing & centering: center nn around zero (use n=−N/2…N/2−1n=-N/2N/2-1) to reduce coefficient coupling.
    • Sampling units: keep a consistent normalized frequency (cycles/sample) vs rad/sample; παn2n^2 vs α2n2 n^2 conventions can trip you up.
    • Noise: average PHAF over multiple τ; use robust WLS in the unwrapping method.
    • Multiple components: apply deflation—estimate strongest, subtract, then repeat; or use subspace multi-tone extensions.

    If you want, I can drop in compact pseudocode for PHAF+ESPRIT, or tailor the steps to your sampling rate/record length and expected SNR.

Normed Space

Definition 1 - A vector space V over a field 𝕂 (especially, ℝ or ℂ) is a set of vectors which comes with an addition + : V × V → V and scalar multiplication ⋅ : 𝕂 × V → V, along with some axioms: Commutativity, Associativity, Identity, and inverse of addition, identity of multiplication, and distributivity.

Axioms

  • Associativity of vector addition: u + (v + w) = u + v + w.
  • Commutativity of vector addition: u + v = v + u.
  • Identity Element of vector addition: ∃0 ∈ V s.t. 0 + v = v, ∀v ∈ V.
  • Inverse Element of vector addition: ∀v ∈ V, there exists −v ∈ V, s.t. v + (−v) = 0.
  • Compatibility of scalar multiplication with field multiplication: ∃0 ∈ V s.t. a(bv) = (ab)v.
  • Identity Element of scalar multiplication: ∃1 ∈ 𝕂 s.t. 1v = v, ∀v ∈ V.
  • Distributivity of scalar multiplication with respect to the vector addition: a(u + v) = au + av.
  • Distributivity of vector addition with respect to the scalar multiplication: (a + b)v = av + bv.

Examples

  • ℝn, ℂn, C([0, 1]).

Definition 2 - A vector space V is finite-dimensional if every linearly independent set is a finite set. In other words, for all sets E ⊆ V such that E has a finite cardinality. V is infinite-dimensional if it is not finite-dimensional.

Definition 3 - A norm on the vector space V is a function ‖⋅‖ : V → [0, ∞) satisfying the following three properties:

  • (Definiteness) ‖v‖ = 0 if and only if v = 0.
  • (Homogeneity) ‖λv‖ = |λ|‖v‖ for ∀v ∈ V and λ ∈ 𝕂.
  • (Triangle Inequality) ‖v1 + v2‖ ≤ ‖v1‖+‖v2‖ for ∀v1, v2 ∈ V.

A seminorm is a function ‖⋅‖ : V → [0, ∞) which satisfies (Homogeneity) and (Triangle Inequality) but not necessarily (Definiteness). A vector space equipped with a norm is called a normed space.

Definition 4 - A metric d : X × X → [0, ∞) is defined to follow the three conditions:

  • (Identification) d(u, v) = 0 if and only if u = v.
  • (Symmetry) d(u, v) = d(v, u).
  • (Triangle Inequality) d(u, v) + d(v, w) ≥ d(u, w) for all u, v, w ∈ V.

Proposition 5 - Let ‖⋅‖ be a norm on a vector space V. Then d(u, v) = ‖u − v‖ defines a metric on V, which we call metric induced by the norm.

Example

  • Euclidean norm on ℝn or ℂn is given by ‖x‖2 = (∑i|xi|2)1/2 with ‖x‖∞ = maxi|xi|, ‖x‖p = (∑i|xi|p)1/p for 1 ≤ p < ∞

  • sandwiching: the norms are essentially equivalent.

Definition 6 - Let X be a metric space, The vector space C∞(X) is defined as C∞(X) = {f : X → ℂ : f is continuous and bounded}.

Example

  • C∞([0, 1]) is C([0, 1]).

Proposition 7 - For any metric space X, a norm on the vector space C∞(X) is defined as ‖u‖∞ = supx ∈ X|u(x)|. Definition 8 - un is uniformly convergent to u on X, un → u in C∞(X), if limn → ∞‖un − u‖∞ = 0 or ∀ε > 0, ∃N ∈ ℕ : ∀n ≥ N, ∀x ∈ X, |un(x) − u(x)| < ε. Example

  • The sequence is in lp for all p > 1 but not in p = 1.

Definition 10 - A normed space is a Banach space if it is complete with respect to the metric induced by the norm.

Theorem 11 - For any metric space X, the space of bounded, continuous functions on X is complete, and thus C∞(X) is a Banach space.
